column168: Shipment offered as an empty "Dry Shipper" by courier.  Upon closer inspection, CO employees noticed "empty" container had inner container with light displays and wires resembling a bomb.  Employees notified manager on duty.  Manager on duty immediately contacted police with possible bomb on premises.     Police responded and found paperwork inside of outerpackage indicating shipment was actually a Diagnostic Specimens UN3373 in a "Dry Shipper" with temperature readout.    Police deemed situation non threatening and left facility.    Police report requested by CO management.    Local FAA Hazardous Materials Security inspectior advised of undeclared hazmat and ER.
column169: No recommendations or actions    Employees addressed preceived threat properly by notifying local management and Emergency Responders.

column168: LEAKING PACKAGE WAS CALLED IN TO DMP CONTAING A FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND LABEL RESPONDER RETRIEVED PACKAGE AND RETURNED TO DMP.

PACKAGE WAS LEAKING INTERNALLY FROM SORT AISLE. PACKAGE CONTENTS PERMEATED PACKAGE AND BEGAN TO LEAK ON TO THE BELT SYSTEM BEFORE IT REACHED THE BELT PICK-OFFS. HAZARDOUS LIQUID CONTAMINATED BOTH TOP AND BOTTOM OF BELT THAT RUNS ABOVE   LOWEST BELTLIINE. PICK-OFFS TURNED OFF BELT AND NOTIFIED DESIGNATED RESPONDER. AREA WAS CORDENED OFF FROM NON-RESPONDING EMPLOYEES. RESPONDER DONNED FULL PPE AND RETRIEVED THE DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS. IDENTIFIED CONTENTS AND FOLLOWED   CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET CHEMICAL WAS PHED AT A 1 ON THE PH SCALE. RESPONDER NEUTRALIZED LIQUID WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE. RESPONDER WAS UNABLE TO NEUTRALIZE CORROSIVE ON BOTTOM OF UPPER BELT. CHAIN OF COMMAND WAS THEN INITIATED AND AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS THEN CALLED IN TO NEUTRALIZE AND DISPOSE. SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ALL EQUIPMENT, RESPONDER PPE, AND WALKING SURFACES WERE DECONTAMINATED.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While loading, one 3,900 milliliter carton was punctured by the forklift.  Approximately 2,900 milliliters of free product were released and impacted the dock and the trailer.  BAX Global personnel performed the cleanup using gloves and vermiculite.  The cleanup materials and damaged carton with entire contents were placed into a 5-gallon salvage drum pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 10/05/2006 Oak Harbor driver Randy Monnier picked up one plastic tote of Hydrochloric Acid at GriffinBrothers. Griffin Brothers is located within one half mile from the Oak Harbor terminal. The Hydrochloric Acid was contained in a plastic tote, which was protected by a metal cage.      After loading the driver proceeded directly to the Oak Harbor terminal and upon arrival noticed that the tote had began to leak. Griffin Brothers was called immediately and due to their close proximity resronded to contain and clean up the spill. The spill was restricted to the location that the truck was parked at and there was no run-off into storm or other drainage. This area is paved with asphalt.      Griffin Brothers personnel used soda ash to neutralize the entire product that had spilled. They eilso pumped the remainder of the product from the leaking tote into another tote and returned both to their bu iness. They also used soda ash to neutralize any acid within the trailer. They estimated that amount of the spill was 15 to 25 gallons and total duration of this spill was approximately one hour and 15 minutes. Total cleanup lasted about 3 hours from the start of the incident.      It appeared that something had been stacked on top of the tote at some point prior to shipment with Oak Harbor and this had caused the cracks in the top of the tote. There were three cracks and breaks in the tote apparently all caused by compression. Two cracks were in the top of the tote at the edge and were approximately 3” -4” long. One other crack was near a corner and ran down the side of the tote approximately 4”.
column169: The driver, prior to the shipper loading these articles into the trailer, should do better inspection of totes. A safety bulletin will be sent to all terminals outlining this situation and instructing all drivers that they need to carefully inspect these types of totes and what they should be looking for specifically prior to accepting the shipment.

column168: On Tuesday, October 17, 2006, a Veolia driver was dispatched to pick up a hazardous materials shipment from Array Biopharma located in Boulder, CO for delivery to the Veolia, Henderson Colorado facility later that afternoon.  The driver arrived with the shipment at the Veolia, Henderson facility at approximately 4:30 PM on Tuesday, October 17, 2006, and was put into temporary storage to be received on Wednesday, October 18, 2006.    At approximately 8:00 AM on October 18, 2006 the receiving crew at the Veolia, Henderson facility  began unloading the containers from the trailer.  It was at this time that the tote was discovered to be leaking.  The receiving crew immediately notified the facility EH&S Manager of the leak.  Within minutes of the investigation, approximately 280 gallons was shown to missing from the tote.  The material had leaked out of the trailer onto the soil beneath it.      After review of the shipping document, the RQ of 100 pounds was identified for a D001 hazardous waste characteristic.  The NRC and the Colorado Department of Public Health & Environment (CDPHE) were then immediately notified. This was approximately 8:15 AM.      Veolia then arranged for a contractor to remediate soil.  Approximately 17 yard of soil was excavated from the spill. Soil samples have been taken and sent to a laboratory for analysis as directed by CDPHE.  The area will be cleaned to the Colorado Soil remediation standards.  All contaminated soils will be sent for proper hazardous waste disposal.     After investigating the tote, it was noted the fill valve on the bottom of the tote was not completely shut, and the gasket was missing from the valve cap.  The receiving crew shut the valve and replaced the gasket, which caused the leak to stop.
column169: The incident will be reviewed with the Veolia driver and Array Biopharma to ensure that all future containers are closed in a manner which conform to the applicable requirements of the specification in addition to the information contained in the manufacturer's notification as directed by 173.24(f).

column168: The box was crushed by the FMC loader used for TJLDs, in the scissor lift. The outer box and inner container known as a PIG were crushed. The inner PIG contain 70 radioactive seeds used to treat various types of cancer. All but approximately 16 seeds were recovered. A seed is approximately the diameter of pencil lead for a mechanical pencil. The State of Washington was notified, the TSA, Airport Police & Fire Depts, and the FAA were notified. I spoke to SA Don Stiger. It is believed that the remaining seeds were collected by ground cleaners and disposed of. The half life of these seeds are nine days. Dr Roy Parker, the Radiophysiist for FedEx Corp consulted on this matter.

column168: At approximately 9:00 am on November 25, 2006 a tanker trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, (CHES) experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a bulk package.  At the time of the release the driver of the vehicle was completing a loading operation at Vanderbilt Chemical located in Bethel, CT.   The tanker truck was loaded with Waste Corrosive Liquid, Flammable n.o.s. (Heptane, Sulfuric Acid) 8, (3), UN 2920, PGII.   While closing the dome hatches and inspecting the valves, the driver notices that the internal valve was leaking through the packing seal at the flange where the pneumatic actuator is located.  The driver immediately notified the onsite contact of the leak and applied vacuum to the tanker to prevent any further discharge of the waste material.   An in house emergency response crew was dispatched to perform any necessary clean up operations and to collect any resulting spill clean up material for future disposal.      Vanderbilt Chemicals also notified CT Department of Environmental Protections of the incident.  Concurrently, CHES driver notified his dispatch of the incident and an alternative tanker was dispatched to the location to transfer the material.       The length of the release was approximately two minutes and approximately 8 oz of the material leaked out onto pavement.      Upon arrival of an alternative tanker, all of the material was transferred without any further incidents.  The damaged tanker was placed out of service until all necessary repairs can be made.
column169: Our initial investigation determined that the rear internal valve packing was damaged and not sealing as designed.  The tanker was placed out of service until all necessary repairs and testing can be performed

column168: On October 3rd 2006 a truck tractor and a non specification cargo tank motor vehicle departed the Cudd Pressure Control, Inc. terminal.  Shortly thereafter it was involved in a roll over motor vehicle accident in Midland County Texas near the city of Odessa, Texas on the Interstate 20 service road and IH-20 shoulder.  The cargo tank was carrying Nitrogen Refrigerated Liquid used in oil field servicing.  The tank released approximately 100 gallons of the hazardous material from the damaged manway into the environment.  The physical properties of the cryogenic liquid causes a cloud vapor when released into ambient temperature.  The liquid is converted into a harmless nitrogen vapor as it is dissipated into the atmosphere.  This cloud, drifting over I-20, caused visibility limitations thus the closing of the west bound lanes of IH-20 for approximately 1 and ½ hours while the tank was emptied.   As reflected on the inspection report hereto attached the inspector stated that the release was due to damage of the manway, which occurred when the interior tank shifted upon impact with the ground.
column169: It is the concern of Cudd Pressure Control, Inc. that the requirement for this report was produced at the direction of local authorities to accomplish a controlled release of a cloud vapor producing material which caused visibility limitation on IH-20 and required the closure of this transportation artery in excess of the regulatory limit for reporting.  As always improved training and improvements in operational procedures reduce these events.  Technology does not provide a better package at this time, except for specification tanks and the hazardous material involved in this event under certain conditions does not require a specification tank.  Those conditions were present at the time of this event.

column168: Shipment was sent without declaring the non-DG properly.  Shipment was more than 1000 kilos and shrinkwrapped to a skid therefore not screened by Cargo agents at British Airways Seattle. Cargo was loaded onto BA flight 48/5Oct.    Upon arrival and delivery to the Cargo building in London, one box of the above airwaybill was found leaking. There was a label stating "Non Spillable Battery", and another label stating "GEN2 Power Unit Single Briggs". The box was opened and found that it was powered by a "Briggs and Stratton Petrol Motor" but the tank was empty. There are 3 units according to the invoice. The Power Units were not declared under UN3166 Engine Internal Combustion(flammable liquid powered Not Restricted as per Special Provision A70, and what type of Non Spillable Battery used. This information was not to be found on any documentation from PDX.
column169: This was not due to failure on the part of British Airways.  This issue should be taken up with the shipper on proper declaration of goods.

column168: THERE WERE A FEW POSSIBLE CAUSES.  THERE WAS AN 4P STACKED PALLET NOT SECURED THAT FELL OVER ON TO THE DAMAGED PALLET.  THE PALLET THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS RESTING ON WAS BROKEN INTO TWO.  THE PALLET SITTING IN FRONT OF THE DAMAGED ONE WAS PRESSING THE DAMAGED FREIGHT.  AND FINALLY EACH PIECE ON THE DAMAGED PALLET WAS HEAVY AND THE FREIGHT MAY HAVE COLLAPSED UNDER ITS OWN PRESSURE.
column169: SECURE ALL FREIGHT WELL.  NOT JUST HM PALLETS BUT ALL SURROUNDING PALLETS.  INSPECT THE PALLETS FOR ANY SHARP PROTRUDING OBJECTS OR ANYTHING ELSE THAT MAY CAUSE DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT.  USE PALLETS DUNNAGE AND LOAD DECKS IN BETWEEN PALLETS WITH HM AND DRUMS TO PREVENT PUNCTURES.

column168: Employee loaded the skid of cylinders onto trailer (3 cylinders laying on their side banded to a wooden pallet). Employee then proceeded to install a load lock bar in order to close and seal the trailer. Since the cylinders were at approximate eye leve, the employee noticed slight misting at the head of one of the cylinders. This was at appoximately 0320. Employee immediately proceeded to get his supervisor (myself). Once notified, I obtained the copy of the shipping orders, saw what the product was, and immediately closed the door on the trailer. I then had the trailer removed from the dock, and had it placed in the yard farthest away from any housing, etc. After having called my Regional Safety Manager, Chemtrec was called (as instructed on the B.O.L.), and the contracted emergency response agency was called (ERS of Ohio, Inc.).  Upon inpection emergency response team (on the cylinder in question), it was found that the valve was off seat by 1/4 of a turn- allowing seapage of gases. The ERS team then closed the valve, recapped the cylinder, and ventilated the trailer for 45 minutes.Due to the nature of the release of gases, the duration of the release is unknown.

At this point a supervisor was notified and the carton was opened by the supervisor for inspection. It was discovered that there was tape on the cap. The supervisor did not check to see if the cap was loose, but instead placed the cartin into a recovery drum.

At the time the shipment was being unloaded, our employee noticed several cartons had wet marks on them. After further investigation, it was determined that at some point during transportation, something heavy was stacked on top of this shipment. This resulted in extra pressure being placed on the cartons (and plastic jugs inside), which in turn forced the corrosive liquid out of the caps, which were not completely tight on the jugs.

column168: On October 8, 2006, at approximately 4:41 CDT,the trailer of a vehicle operated by KLLM Transport Services experienced a load shift while in transport. As a result approximately 7 gallons of the material was released onto the trailer flooring.  At approximately 5:26 pm CDT, KLLM Transport Services retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental clean up operations. Based on the information provided the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Patriot Environmental (Patriot) to perform the corrective actions. The crew from Patriot arrived on-site and assessed the scope of the release. The crew began corrective actions by opening the trailer doors to ventilate the released material prior to entering the trailer. Once the trailer had ventilated the crew entered the trailer and inspected the drums. One of the 55-gallon drums was found to be rusted and damaged. They overpacked the damaged drum. The flooring was wiped clean and the drums including the overpack were secured on the trailer.

column168: DAVISON FUELS TRUCK DRIVER WAS AT DELIVERY LOCATION (AN INDEPENDENT RETAIL GASOLINE STATION)TO DELIVER A LOAD OF GASOLINE. DRIVER GAUGED THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS AND WAS UNSURE IF ALL PRODUCT ORDERED WOULD FIT IN TANK. HE QUESTIONED STATION EMPLOYEE WHO TOLD HIM IT SHOULD FIT BUT UNABLE TO CONFIRM AS THERE WAS NOT A CALIBRATION CHART AT STATION FOR THE TANK. DRIVER PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT INTO THE TANK. PRODUCT DID NOT FIT TANK OVER FLOWED THROUGH  A MONITOR OPENING WHICH HAD A TOP SEAL CAP ON IT. THE TOP SEAL CAP FAILED TO CONTAIN PRODUCT AS IT HAD FAILED TO SEAL THE OPENING DUE TO DETERIORATION DUE TO AGE AND/OR CORROSION.DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM TRUCK TO TANK, AND THEN CONTAINED PRODUCT, AND FIRE DEPAREMTN WAS CALLED FOR SAFETY AND ASSISTANCE. DAVISON FUELS PERSONNEL ALSO RESPONDED TO SCENE FOR CLEAN UP. DURATION OF RELEASE ESTIMATED TO BE UNDER ONE MINUTE.
column169: SPILL WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURED IF THE TOP SEAL CAP ON THE MONITOR PORT HAD NOT FAILED. THE CAP WAS IN SUCH BAD CONDITION AS IT WOULD NOT SEAL PORT.    STATION OWNERS/OPERATIONS SHOULD INSPECT TANKS AND THEY SHOULD ALWAYS HAVE CALIBRATION CHARTS ON HAND AT STATIONS AVAILABLE FOR DRIVERS TO BE ABLE TO CHECK CAPACITY TO HOLD PRODUCT.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines (FRTL) driver was travelling southbound on Highway 247 in the right lane.  Three passenger vehicles were making U-turns from NB 247 to SB 247.  The first two passenger vehicles turned into the right lane in front of the FRTL truck.  FRTL driver switched to left lane to avoid passenger vehicles.  Vehicle 3, a small pickup truck, made a U-turn into left southbound lane directly in front of FRTL truck.  FRTL swerved left to avoid vehicle 3.  FRTL truck and tanker became unstable and rolled over onto right side, the rear portion of the tanker impacted the bed of the pickup truck.  Tanker ruptured and approximately 4500 gallons of diesel was spilled.  Macon-Bibb County Fire Dept Hazmat Team responded and dammed the spill with sand.  Remaining fuel in tank was transferred to another tanker and SWS responded to begin cleanup.
column169: Motorists must always be aware of surroundings and faithfully yield right-of way.

column168: Eagle driver pulled into the Kinder Morgan Terminal #1 and pullled up to the left side of a Waccamaw Transport Unit. Our driver's tractor was positioned so that the truck was in a turn to the right. The Waccamaw driver was in the terminal office, another driver for Reliable asked our driver to move so that he could exit the terminal. This driver was leaving without loading his truck. Our driver looked in his right side miror and could not see the other unit beside him, he could see it through the spot mirror but it did not give him the information he needed to determine if he had enough clearence. He then decided to move forward and when he did he struck the left rear corner of the other vehicle bending the bumper, light box and mudflap assembly. Our unit had a load head for the #3 compartment broken off and about 10 gallons of product came out onto the asphalt driveway.
column169: Management meet with the driver to discuss this incident. The driver went through Smith System Training.

column168: Inbound BNSF train inspection in railyard revealed entrained TILX 290329 dripping product from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) at the rate of 3 drops per minute. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder reported finding the BOV bottom operating handle not pinned and slightly open. The handle retainer bracket was also missing. Responder moved the BOV operating handle to the closed position, ending the product drips by 1350 hrs. MDT, 10/12/06. The operating handle was tied down. The bottom outlet gasket was not checked. All spillage evaporated. TILX 290329 was released and allowed to proceed to its destination without being setout from the train that it arrived on.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: LTCX 1918 entrained in a BNSF outbound train in the railyard was reported with ice build-up and liquid dripping from the equipment or operating compartment of this tank car. A BNSF mechanical-hazardous material responder removed the Praxair seals and found the discharge valve partially open and this valve’s turn-buckle and spring-tensioned valve tie-down had become dislodged. The valve tie-down assembly came apart in two pieces. Responder closed the valve, reassembled the tie-down apparatus and applied the tie-down retainer on the closed wheel valve. A bungee cord was also applied as an added valve tie-down to prevent the valve from vibrating open again. Within 20 minutes the ice began to melt and recede. With no further leakage detected, LTCX 1918 was released to proceed to its destination. Response concluded by 2020 hrs. PDT, 10/06/06.

column168: A ERA Inspector performing an outbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard, reported entrained GATX 201204 emanating product odor. A BNSF mechanical-hazardous material responder inspected GATX 201204 finding no securement exceptions; although, a slight product odor was present when the protective housing cover was opened. GATX 201204 was setout from the train consist and moved to the isolated containment area for further inspection. Later on 10/03/06, shipper contract responders inspected GATX 201204 and bubble tested the 280.5 psi Midland pressure relief valve (PRD). This PRD was last tested in 2005 by CACA and reinspection due in 2010. The bubble test indicated an intermittent release of vapor from the PRD. The responders then checked the condition of the upper 0-ring, finding the 0-ring edge slightly curled on 2/3’s of the ring’s circumference. This o-ring was flipped over and reinstalled. After the PRD was resecured, no detectable vapor or odor registered on the responder’s calibrated air monitoring device. Response was concluded by 1915 hrs. CDT, 10/03/06. GATX 202204 was diverted to the GATX rail shop in Kansas City, MO. for PRD repair and recertification.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: GATX 201499 was reported in the railyard emanating product odor and soon afterwards GATX 201499 was moved and isolated in the railyard. BNSF and contract responders inspected GATX 201499. No product odor was detectable from ground level, but product odor was detected near the protective housing cover. The initial inspection of all valves and fittings determined that all were secure. The 280.5 psi Midland pressure relief valve (PRD) was inspected and bubble tested for leaks. The bubble test indicated that the PRD had a slight leak. No repairs were attempted at this time. The FRA was contacted for movement waiver to the consignee’s facility, approximately 20 miles north of Willmar, MN. The BNSF responder monitored GATX 201499 through-out the night. On 10/03/06, a BNSF special train, shadowed by the BNSF responder, transported GATX 201499 to the consignee’s facility for unloading, without further incident.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: During the investigation of an LPG odor in the railyard that was reported by a BNSF train crew, GATX 40201 was inspected by BNSF responders. GATX 40201 was emanating an intermittent product odor near the manway area. Detailed inspection revealed that 2 of 8 manway securement bolts were less that tool tight. In addition, the manway nozzle gasket was found to be cut at the area near the manway hinges. A new replacement gasket was installed and the manway cover was secured by properly tool tightening all the manway securement bolts. GATX 40201 was monitored during the subsequent railyard movement with no indication of any product odor release. Response concluded by 1321 hrs. PDT, 10/02/06.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman inspecting railcars scheduled for an outbound train in the railyard, observed UTLX 208108 leaking product from the top valve housing area. UTLX 208108 was carefully moved to the railyard containment area for further inspection. BNSF contract responders found the liquid line valve partially open. Also, the closure plugs for the liquid and vapor valves were less than tool tight. The contract responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened the loose closure plugs. On Sunday, October 1, 2006, a CSX Transportation Yard Crew working in Cayce, South Carolina reported that Tank Car UTLX48211 was emitting a strong odor and had signs of possible product on sides of the container. The area was immediately isolated and CSX Management implemented their emergency response plan. Chemtrec was notified (report number 10012006012) and the shipper, Exxonmobil was informed of the release. Hepaco Environmental was contacted to respond and secure the container. Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the vacuum relief device inoperable and stuck in the open (down) position. Hepaco utilized wooden wedges to force the vacuum relief device in the closed (up) position until proper repairs could be arranged. This action temporarily secured the tank car from releasing vapors. On Monday, October 2nd Exxonmobil contacted Rescar to inspect and replace the defective valve. Rescar responded to the site, inspected the tank car, and ordered the correct replacement parts. Rescar representatives returned to Cayce Yard on Tuesday, October 3rd and replaced the valve with a plug at the request of the shipper. They also performed a leak test of the container. After completion, the car was released to destination.       Cause Code: 462     NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0)= 32

column168: The brakes on a tractor-trailer hauling tote bags of polymeric beads caught fire.  The driver attempted to put the fire out with a fire extinguisher but was unable to prevent the fire from spreading to the trailer. The driver contacted the local authorities who mobilized a hazmat team for response to the fire and hazmat containment.  At approximately 20:40 CST, the hazmat team recommended that the Shelby County Sheriff's office evacuate all residences within 1/2 mile of the incident and allow the product to burn.  The Texas Highway Patrol also closed Hwy. 59 in both directions.  At approximately 22:20, 3-A foam was applied to the fire which was suppressed by 22:35.  At 23:00 the local authorities were advised that evacuees could be reinstated to their homes.  At aproximately 23:30 the two northbound lanes were converted into two way traffic to open the roadway.  The hazmat team immediately mobilized equipment to remove the remains of the trailer and burned product (all a total loss), to vacuum up contaminated water that had accumulated in the dry drainage ditch and to excavate contaminated soil.  The environmental cleanup was completed within 22 hours of the start of the incident.

THE TRAILER DOOR WAS SMOKING DUE TO THE MATERIAL INVOLVED (CRYOGENICEVAPORATION AND CONDENSATION) AND A DRIVER FROM ANOTHER COMPANY CALLED 911. POLICE AND VOLUNTEER FIREMEN FROM NEIGHBORING COMMUNTIES RESPONDED. BOC GASES SENT A CRYOGENIC TECHNICIAN TO GIVE PROPER INSTRUCTION ON HANDLING OF THE RELEASE. THE FIRE DEPT HAZMAT SQUAD ALSO RESPONDED AND ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE RELEASE WHICH WAS EMANATING FROM THE VALVE ON THE CYLINDER. THE ATTEMPTS TO STOP THE RELEASE AT THE VALVE WERE UNSUCCESSFUL DUE TO THE VALVE BEING FROZEN. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE RELEASED FROM THE CYLINDER. THE EVACUATION WAS INITIATED BY THE VOLUNTEER FIREMEN AND WAS CALLED OFF AFTER KNOWLEDGABLE CREWS WERE ONSCENE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AND THE TRAILER LEFT THE SCENE AFTER CONTENTS WERE RELEASED.   ALL PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.
column169: RESPONSIBLE ASSOCIATE(S) HAVE BEEN SHOWN PROPER FREIGHT HANDLING AND LOADING TECHNIQUES AS WELL AS RECERTIFICATION FOR FORKLIFT OPERATION IF NECESSARY.

column168: On October 15th at 10:30 hours, a CSX Transportation employee working in Hamlet Yard observed signs of fresh product on the sides and odor being emitted from Tank Car DUPX29152 (Load - Methanol). CSX Management immediately implemented their emergency response plan and the tank car was isolated. Chemtrec was notifed of the incident (report number 10152006007) and the shipper, Dupont was informed of the release. Hepaco Environmental was contacted to respond and secure the container. Once on site, Hepaco representatives found that the cause of the release was due to one of four liquid line mounting flange bolts/nuts was less than tool tight. Hepaco representatives properly tightened all the mounting flange bolts/nuts using a wrench in a criss cross pattern then the car was checked for leaks. Once properly secured the tank car was released to destination. Approximately two (2) gallons of product was released from the container.  Cause Code: 270  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)= 80

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: This incident occurred in the customer (delivery site, the Golden Moon Casino) parking lot.  Failure in rear of tanker well, between the sump and tank shell.  3/18" hole developed and hypochlorite material leaked for 10 minutes before hole plugged by driver, and then fire response plugged with their equipment 10 minutes after that to secure it.  Once plug secured, additional tanker brought to the scene and product was transferred from defective tanker to extra tanker.  Fire department cleaned-up spill on ground along with company contracted environmental clean-up firm.  Release mitigated.      Fire department on scene, report was completed by Captin Taylor.  It was the Choctaw Fire Department.  MS DEP or EPD also showed-up at the scene (MS Emergency Mgmt. was notified of the incident, report number is Eris King - person we spoke to).
column169: Company has been in the process over the last three years of replacing older, cargo tankers with liners with fiberglass tankers (MC 412, DOT SP # 10878, 12516 and 11903).  Fiberglass units have greater longevity, less suspect to corrosion, no liners (and hence no opportunity for sudden liner failure) and are better suited overall for hypochlorite service.  We just have to continue on that path of eventually changing out all tankers in our fleet.  This was a newer Polar tanker, hence why it had not been replaced to date (it also had passed its inspections in April).

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, a BNSF switch crew reported a liquid slosh from the manway area of GATX 18284 when they coupled into the railcars in the track that GATX 18284 was on. This switch crew also reported a strong odor emanating from GATX 18284 and this tank car was cordoned-off in the railyard. All operations within 150 feet of GATX 18284 were ceased. GATX 18284 was inspected by consignee responders. Responders reported finding 3 manway swing bolts not applied and the other 3 manway securement bolts finger loose. Remnants of the manway gasket appeared fixed around the rim of the manway lid. The deteriorated condition of the gasket prevented a good seal. Responders installed a new gasket, applied and tool tightened all manway securement bolts. The spillage around the manway and on the tank car shell was wiped. Minimal ground impact was noticed and responders excavated a small amount of impacted soil and ballast that was placed into a 5 gallon plastic bucket for appropriate future disposal. Absorbant material was also applied to other very small ground impact areas. Response was concluded by 1115 hrs. CDT, 10/10/06.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

He said he wasn't sure how much was in the storage tank but it goes to 4' and there was 2 ft in when he started.  He thought product wasn't moving because the sight gauge wasn't moving.  He shut down and checked everything and started up again. He said he was using 8-10 psi with 40' of hose. He said the sight gauge had moved up to 2 1/2 '.   He was standing by the storage tank that was raised off the ground when product shut up out of it and came down on him.  He said he was wearing his nomex, hard hat,faceshield, safety glasses.  He said a few drips got in his right eye.  He immediately went to the shower.  He was taken by ambulance to the hospital, treated and released.
column169: Driver was not following procedures.  He did not have chemical suit and goggles on as required in his work assignment.  Not sure if there was an issue with the sight gauge or there was just too much product and driver didn't go slow enough to allow the sight gauge to keep up.

column168: At approximately 1100 on 10/17/06 TASD train crew notified the control station that the TILX 320020, loaded tank car was leaking from the bottom valve area. column168: BNSF switch foreman reported GATX 60914 leaking in the railyard during switching movement. GATX 60914 was cordoned off in the railyard for further inspection. BNSF contract responders found the 165 psi frangible disc had blown. Responders didn’t have a suitable corrosive service disc with them and decided to replace the failed disc with a 100 psi corrosive service frangible disc so that GATX 60914 could be carefully moved to an isolated area in the railyard until a suitable 165 psi disc could be installed. Responders checked all other top fitting securement and found all to be secure. The spillage was confined to the protective valve housing area and it was neutralized and wiped. Contractor response was concluded by 0730 hrs. MDT, 10/15/06. Shipper was notified to replace the frangible disc with a 165 psi disc before GATX 60914 could be released to proceed to its destination. On 10/18/06, the initial response contractor replaced the 100 psi frangible disc with a new 165 psi frangible disc for corrosive service that was supplied by the shipper. The disc installation was completed by 1100 hrs. MDT without further incident. Afterwards, GATX 60914 was released to proceed to its destination.

column168: This cargo tank motor vehicle was loaded at Kearny, New Jersey and departed approximately 0350 on November 24, 2006 bound for Ward's Island WWTP located in Brooklyn, NY.  As the transport was negotiating a heavy curve entering Bayonne, NJ on US Rt. 440 southbound the driver reports that another truck alongside him left his lane and forced our cargo tank to move over.  Our cargo tank motor vehicle struck a curbing which began the roll-over process.  Our cargo tank motor vehicle landed and remained on the median between southbound and northbound lanes at 0410.  The driver removed himself from his cab and contacted Kuehne.  We dispatched emergency vehicles and an available cargo tank motor vehicle.  When we arrived on-site at 0430 we found the self-closing relief valve would not close and hypochlorite was spilling at a medium rate.  We contained this spill with a large bucket and evacuated the bucket using a small pump to a container effectively stopping the release shortly thereafter.  Berms were set up so as not to allow any more material to enter the storm drains.  The replacement cargo tank motor vehicle was staged alongside and the remaining contents of the damaged cargo tank were transferred.  In all approximately 1500 gallons were recovered.  The New Jersey DEP were on-site and took PH readings at a collection area serving the storm drain.  These readings were neutral due to the tidal action.  Remaining hypochlorite on the roadway was neutralized with citric acid powder.  Kuehne then transported a cargo tank motor vehicle loaded with clean fresh water and the roadway was rinsed to the storm drain.  All material spilled onto the median grassy area was removed using an excavator, loaded onto a roll-off container and will be properly disposed of.  All remediation charges are not in as of yet and the value of total damages listed under question 32 are only estimates.
column169: Kuehne has decided that though our driving staff has an average tenure of almost ten years we will contract with experts in the field of liquid transportation to discuss with the drivers the physics involved with the handling of liquids to include sloshing and transverse free surface effects.    It would be beneficial to undertake a study where innovative and novel designs could be assessed which may result in the relocation of the cargo's center of gravity to a lower position off the roadway.  This would be especially important in the safer handling of higher density materials.    It would be beneficial to utilize rollover testing or simulations for known cargo tank combination designs to assist in the development of radius standards for new highway construction.

At approximately 12:55pm on October 24, 2006 a van trailer stored at Clean Harbors Environmental Services 10-day in-transit storage yard located in El Dorado, AR experienced a minor release of hazardous waste material from a non-bulk package. An employee at the location noticed small amount of material seeping through the van trailer floor.  He immediately notified his supervisor of the spill and an in house emergency response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to take all necessary corrective actions.  Upon review of the paperwork, the emergency response crew donned appropriate protective equipment and entered the trailer.  An inspection of the non-bulk packages in the trailer identified that a single 55-gallon UN 1A1 container of Class 9 liquid experienced a failure at the seam of the container located near the top third of the drum.  The response crew immediately used a chemically compatible absorbent material to contain approximately 10 gallons of liquid that was release to the floor of the trailer.   The leaking drum was placed in a suitable salvage drum and all of the absorbent was collected and placed into appropriate container for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.   Approximately one quart of material leaked through the floorboards of the van-trailer onto gravel and compacted dirt pad.  The contaminated area was excavated, the material placed into appropriate containers for disposal at an approved hazardous waste management facility.     The time frame from the initial notice of the spill until the drum was overpacked and the spill clean up was approximately 2 hours.  All of the released material was collected and no offsite impact occurred.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was deterioration of the container on storage and insufficient inspection prior to transportation.    The individuals responsible for preparing this shipment for transportation will be informed of this incident and a request will be made to the involved parties to undergo additional training on container inspections.

column168: BNSF operations personnel were advised by a BNSF train crew that they detected a LPG odor in the middle of the railyard near track 6. Train traffic was suspended and all personnel were notified to stay clear of the odor source area. BNSF responders reviewed the track lists and identified two tank cars with potential of the odor source. Inspection of one of these tank cars, CRPX 9704, revealed that the sample line was leaking due to the valve plug being improperly installed on the riser nipple. The valve was closed, but the valve assembly appeared to be cross-threaded, since it was at an angle to the nipple, rather than straight and inline. Evaluation of the corrective options determined that the immediate delivery of CRPX 9704 to the consignee, less than 20 miles away, was one of the safest options. The consignee was contacted and agreed to accept CRPX 9704 for immediate unloading. An emergency movement waiver was sought from the FRA; however the FRA advised that none was required due to the short distance to destination and the small amount of product that could be released into the atmosphere. BNSF responders concluded response by 1215 hrs. PDT, 10/02/06. Rail traffic commenced at 1320 hrs. PDT, 10/02/06. CRPX 9704 was delivered and placed at the consignee’s facility for unloading by 1030 hrs. PDT, 10/03/02 without further incident.

column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, S. MICHAEL AUSTIN, RECEIVED A CALL FROM MECH. FOREMAN TOPOLSKI UTLX 68995 HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP OF CAR. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ALL OVER THE SIDE OF CALL AND LEAKING DOWN ON THE GROUND. THE CAR LOCATED IN THE CSX CURTIS BAY YARD. CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPATCHED PERMA-FIX MARYLAND (A&A ENVRIONMENTAL) TO RESPOND. HAZ-MAT MANAGER, S. MICHAEL AUSTIN, ALSO RESPONDED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL MANWAY COVER LID WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THE CARE WAS CLEANED OFF BY CONTRACTOR AND THE MANWAY GASKET REPLACED AND ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.    CAUSE CODE=200 AND 219    NARRI= 5(5+1+0)(3+0)=90

column168: The pallet was being unloaded by the dsr, after picking up with the forklift the material began to escape from the drum. The dsr notified me (David King, FOS) and was instructed to get some floor dry to contain the spill. After about 30 seconds had elapsed the driver returned and immediately began to cover the spill to contain it. Meanwhile, the shrink wrap was cut and the drum was laid on it’s side to prevent further spillage. The pallet was broken under the plastic drum which caused the drum to be cut when the fork was raised and pinched the drum between it and the pallet. This resulted in a cut apprx. 7 inches long at the base of the drum. The spill was contained as quickly as possible and the clean up followed.
column169: My recommendation in this incident would be to use thin plywood or heavy cardboard underneath the drums to prevent them from falling through a broken pallet.

column168: On Thursday October 26, 2006 Shipment was inspected per TSA requirements in JFK for international export.  AWB 006-6098-6030, 1 piece to MIL.  The package was identified as containing ORM-D material and was not described as hazardous material.  Shipment was not transported, damaged, or leaking.  The shipment was quarantined and JFK notified DL's Corporate DG group (DGMG) via our internal notification system.  The local Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) office in JFK has been notified and has inspected the shipment.  Delta was given ok to return package to customer and it was released.
column169: The shipment appeared to have been prepared as ORM-D, a class of material not allowed by Delta. Delta requires shipments to be reclassified as  Consumer Commidity for acceptance.

column168: MOTOR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HWY 144 IN BOONE COUNTY, IA.  MV CARRYING/LOADED WITH 7500 GALLONS ETHANOL ALCOHOL.  MV ATTEMPTED TO NEGOTIATE A LEFT HAND TURN IN HIGHWAY WHEN APPARENTLY A MECHANICAL FAILURE OCCURRED WITH THE TRAILER’S SUSPENSION – A POSSIBLE BROKEN SUSPENSION RIGHT FRONT MAIN SPRING. THE MV WAS FORCED TO THE SHOULDER & SUBSEQUENTLY OVER THE EMBANKMENT CAUSING MV TO OVER TURN RUPTURING THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF TRAILER.  DRIVER SUFFERED A BROKEN NECK HOWEVER ALIVE THANKS TO SEATBELT. ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT 10:15 A.M. & REMAINING PRODUCT ON TRAILER WAS NOT COMPLETELY PUMPED OUT UNTIL 10:00 P.M. THAT EVENING. WRECKER REMOVED MV FROM ACCIDENT SCENE BY 11:30 P.M. THAT EVENING. CONTAMINATION CLEAN UP IS BEING COMPLETED BY ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY OVERSEEN BY IOWA DNR. FRONT AXLE OF THE TRAILER CAME UNATTACHED FROM SUSPENSION TO MV LEAVING THE DRIVING SURFACE.
column169: NEWER TRAILERS TO HAUL ETHANOL, GASOLINE & DIESEL ARE 406’S.  WE HAVE IN THE PAST & WILL CONTINUE IN THE FUTURE TO THOROUGHLY INSPECT SUSPENSION PARTS – ESPECIALLY SPRINGS.

column168: VI. At 6:12 a.m. on October 14, 2005 Eric Smith from Great Lakes Petroleum Corporation received a call from a driver stating that he had had a spill at a station. Eric then sent a cleanup company over to the site and proceeded to the site himself. When Eric arrived at the site he discovered that the hose had come off the tank during the unloading process spilling product on to the pavement and in to the drains. Inland Waters handled the clean up.
column169: VII. The driver had been trained on how to properly unload product. He chose to ignore the training that had been provided to him. He did not take the time to make sure the fitting was properly attached to the tank before beginning to unload product. The driver as terminated from Great Lakes Petroleum for multiple safety violations regarding this incident.

column168: Driver was preparing to unload product from railcar to trailer through the B side liquid valve when he noticed a slight odor from the valve area.  He closed the valve and notified his supervisor. Two employees went to the site and tried to tighten the packing nut but were unable to do so.  They placed a wet cloth over the valve to absorb vapors and the driver resumed unloading through the A side valve.  The car was emptied of product into trailers that day and the car was degassed.  Less than 5 pounds of vapor were estimated to have been released. No evacuations were made, no injuries were reported and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

SHIPPER DID NOT SHRINKWRAP THE SHIPMENT ADEQUATELY THEREFORE CAUSING THE SHIPMENT TO FALL.  SHIPPER HAS BEEN CALLED AND WE ARE TRYING TO DETERMINE WHO WILL BE CHARGED FOR THE DISPOSAL.  CON-WAY CLEANED THE SPILL BY CONTAINING THE SHIPMENT INTO 2 10 GALLON DRUMS AND 1 50 GALLON DRUM.
column169: CON-WAY WILL CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND SPEAK WITH THEM ABOUT PROPER SHIPPING TECHNIQUES FOR THE FUTURE.

ACTUAL CONTENTS OF THE BOX ARE AS FOLLOWS:    6EA P/N 802300-14 PBE CONTAINING O2 GENERATOR, CHEMICAL  4EA P/N E28180-10 PBE CONTAINING 02 GENERATOR, CHEMICAL
AFTER FINDING CARTON ON TRL PUT IN SALVAGE DRUM
column169: FRT SHOULD HAVE SECURED BETTER ON TRL

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS INCORRECTLY LOADED AT ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER, THERE WAS HEAVY FREIGHT STACKED ON TOP OF IT WITHOUT THE USE OF ANY DUNNAGE, ONE CAN WAS CRUSHED, PROBABLY IN TRANSIT BUT DID NOT GET NOTICED UNTIL THE NEXT BUSINESS DAY.
column169: NEED TO PRACTICE SAFER LOADING HABITS, THE USE OF DUNNAGE AND BE AWARE OF WHAT IS BEING LOADED TO PREVENT THE SAME THING HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: WHEN BREAKING A TRAILER THERE WERE 8 DAMAGED PAILS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THESE WERE DAMAGED IN TRANPSORT. THE 8 PAILS WERE RECOUPED IN HAZMAT DRUMS. THE CAUSE OF THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO LACK OF BLOCKING BRACING AND DUNNAGE.
column169: ALL HAZMAT MUST BE BLOCKED AND BRACED THOROUGHLY.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: While heading north on State Hwy 10, driver reached down on floor for a bottle of water at the same time truck started going off road into gaurd rails. Truck rolled over 3 times ending up adjacent to road. During rollover gaurd rails punctured tank causing it to leak 4302 gallons of fuel oil onto the ground and into reservoir. About 25% went into water. Spill was discovered by DEP Police and was reported to NYS DEC. Three clean up companies were called in along with our spill team. The spill was contained with harbor boom and was cleaned up on water and land with absorbent materials. With in 3 days of spill water was almost fully remediated. Land clean up took over 3 weeks to complete clean up. NYS DEC Spill number is 0608654.
column169: Sense accident our company is in the progress of putting on a "Distracted Driving" campaign. Driver's manager and myself have attended a Rollover and Distracted Driving seminar. Just last week we repeated seminar at our company wide annual safety meeting where over 100 emploees attended. We are also following up with our monthly safety meetings and sending material home with employees in their pay checks.  In the past we have always presented safety meetings regarding distracted driving and have re enforced our no talking on cell phones while driving policy. We are also using this incident to show what can happen (driver srviving) if seat belts are worn, which is another company policy.

column168: TILX 192507 was number 3 of 23 cars involved in a derailment resulting in the loss of approximately 21,748 gallons of material some of which was consumed by fire.   The area was evacuated and the shipper and the appropriate local, state and federal agencies notified. The car was uprighted and the remaining contents was transferred to another railcar for further handling. The damaged car was cleaned, purged and scrapped.   Note: This is 1 of 20 DOT F5800.1 reports submitted for this incident. The evacuation of 150 local residents and mall businesses lasted for about 36 hours when all but about 15 evacuees were allowed to return. The remaining evacuees returned approximately 24 hours later.   Environmental remediation and monitoring is on-going. PKG WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON THE FLOOR OF THE PD-4 BY THE AREA SUPERVISOR. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE CONTACTED THE DMP AND A 12 HR RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE (INCLUDING SILVER SHIELDS). AFTER REFERRING TO THE DECISION TREE AND  APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET (CLASS 8), THE RESPONDER CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL. NEXT THE RESPONDER TRANSPORTED THE CONTAINED PKG AND CONTAMINATED MATERIALS TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DETERIMINED THAT THE CONTAINER  VENT CAP WAS LOOSE, CAUSING SPILLAGE. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND CONTAINER TESTED TO INSURE IT WAS SECURE. THE ENTIRE PKG INCLUDING THE SECURED CONTAINER W/ LIQUID WAS PLACED IN A CLAY ABSORBENT-LINED DMP BAG AND SUBMITTED THROUGH THE DMP  USING THE PROPER HAZ-MAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURE. THE RESPONDER WORE REQUIRED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE), FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, CLEANED UP AND REMOVED THE SPILL SAFELY.
SUPERVISOR NOTICED WET PACKAGE ON BELT AND CONTACTED RESPONDER. DESIGNATED RESPONDER WORE PROPER PPE AND RESPONDED TO SPILL ACCORDING TO DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS.
SKID WAS DOUBLE STACKED, CRUSHING THE BOTTLES INSIDE
DRUM WAS PROPERLY LOADED AND SECURED, LEAKAGE CAME FROM SEAM FAILURE.

A PASSENGER CAR, DRIVEN BY MS LOTTIE SPEERS FULLMORE, SIDE-SWIPED MY TRUCK CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF HIS TRUCK, RESULTING IN AN OVERTURN ACCIDENT.  WHEN MY TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE, IT CAUSED A SMALL RUPTURE AT THE SEAM.  300 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE MEDIAN.  JACKSONVILLE POLLUTION CONTROL (BOB STEPHEN)  WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND REMOVED ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

CARMAN FOUND CAR WITH SOME VAPORS VISIBLE IN THE YARD LIGHTS, WHILE COUPLIING CARS IN DIFFERENT TRAIN. REPORTED TO DISPATCHER WHO NOTIFIED ALL NECESSARY PEOPLE. ARKEMA WAS CALLED TO HELP TAKE CARE OF THIS CAR, BY REPLACING RUPTURED DISC. THIS WAS AN INBOUND EMPTY CAR GOING TO ARKEMA FOR LOADING.

RESPONDED TO A WET PACKAGE. WHILE FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND WEARING PROPER PPE, PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN SPILL TUB AND TAKEN TO THE DMP WORK AREA. WHEN PACKAGE WAS OPENED THERE WAS ANOTHER BOX INSIDE WITH DIAMOND FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABELS ON TWO SIDES. PACKAGE WAS THEN DISPOSED OF USING PROPER PPE AND FOLLOWING DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THE UNDECLARED HAZMAT PROCESS WAS FOLLOWED.

column168: I RESPOND TO A CALL WEARING ALL MY PPE.THERE WERE NO LABELS TO IDENTIFY THAT THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS IN PACKAGE.WHILE PROCESSEING THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER WAS FOUND AND WE NOTIFIED THE HAZARDOUS SUPPORT CENTER. THIS PACKAGE ALSO HAS ISO HEAT ANTI FREEZE, 12 VOLT BATTERY, OIL, ARMOR ALL SPRAY AND WIPES, EXTREME WHEEL CLEANER, CHAIN LUBRICANT, POWER STEERING FLUID, TURTLE WAX, TRAILER HITCH.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. While receiving a shipment it was discovered that apparently, a nail protruding from a pallet had punctured 2 plastic Jerricans. Approximately, 10 gallons of free product was released onto the trailer floor. Southern Waste Services of Pompano Beach, FL was contacted to perform cleanup. Southern Waste Services repalletized 4 affected pallets in the shipment. Southern Waste Services applied speedy dry to the free product on the trailer floor. The spent material was placed into one(1) fifty-five gallon poly drum. BAX Global, Inc. of Fort Lauderdale, FL will coordinate disposal of the waste generated. No injuries or exposures were reported the MSDS was requested.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence

column168: Upon delivery to Lowes DC, one of their forklift operartors forked this drum. The drum released about 35 gallons of product and passing the RQ for this materail. The carrier dispatched a spill contractor to the scene to handle the clean up and to overpack the damaged drum for transit. Lowes sent two of their employees to the hospital to be checked due to possible exposure and were later released back to work.  The carrier notified  the NRC on report# 818892 and notified the OHDEP on report# 0611-32-4262.
column169: The carrier followed up with Lowes on this damage to insure that their loader was instructed on the proper usage of a forklift.

column168: PRODUCT WAS SMASHED BELT THAT WENT WITH SHIPMENT TRANSIT AT DELIVERY LOCATION.
column169: PRODUCT WAS SECURED AT TIME OF DEPARTURE SO DISCUSSED WITH DSR TO ADD EXTRA PROTECTION WHEN HANDLING THIS SIZE CONVEYOR BELTS. WE ADDRESSED THIS AS A GROUP IN WEEKLY COMMUNICATIONS MEETING THE FOLLOWING WEEK. DISCUSSED PROPER PROCEDURES TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THE ORDER WAS LOADED IN FRONT AT 3 HEAVY PALLETS OF METAL.  DURING TRANSIT THE METAL MOVED AGAINST THE DRUM AND RUBBED A HOLE IN THE SIDE.  THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE USED TO PROTECT THE DRUMS FROM THIS DAMAGE.  THERE WAS NO MATERIAL THAT SPILLED OUT AT THE TRAILER.  BSE CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND PLACED IT IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS TIPPED ON ITS SIDE WITH THE HOLE UP TO PREVENT ANY MORE LEAKAGE.
column169: THE ONLY RECOMMENDATION THAT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL WOULD BE TO USE DUNNAGE, SUCH AS PALLETS OR BOARDS.

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-73 CAME TO CURVE IN THE ROAD AND THE RIGHT SIDE WHEELS WENT OFF THE ROAD.  WHEN THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GET TRUCK BACK ON ROAD THE TRUCK WENT INTO THE LEFT (SOUTH BOUND LANE) AND HIT THE GUARD RAIL.  AFTER HITTING THE GUARD RAIL THE TRUCK ROAD ON GUARD RAIL FOR A SEVERAL YARDS THEN IT ROLLED OVER INTO THE DITCH.  MAY HAVE ROLLED AGAIN AND ENDED UP WITH THE TRUCK ON PASSENGER SIDE FACING NORTH.  ON THE TWO FRONT TANKS, THE TOP FILL HOLES HAD OPEN AND SPILLED OUT DIESEL FUEL.  WE DUG OUT THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AFTER THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF AT A LANDFILL.
column169: I REALLY DON'T HAVE ANY SUGGESTIONS FOR CHANGES.  THE DRIVER HAS A VERY GOOD DRIVING RECORD.  OTHER THAN THE FACT THAT THE CRASH AND ROLLOVER CAUSE THE TOP LIDS TO OPEN, STRUCTUALLY THE TRUCK HELD TOGETHER VERY WELL OTHERWISE.

BOTH EMPLOYEES WERE NEAR THE DOOR WHEN IT WAS OPENED, SMELLED SMALL AMOUNT OF THE ODOR FROM THE POISON RELEASE, NEITHER EMPLOYEE TOUCHED THE BOX AND NONE OF THE LIQUID  SPLASHED ON EITHER, BUT BOTH OF THEM DID OBSERVED THE WET BOX. BOTH WERE ADVISED AND DIRECTED TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL TO GET CHECKED OUT. BOTH WERE OBSERVED BY A PHYSICIAN, THEN RELEASED AND RETURNED BACK TO WORK. NO FOLLOW-UP VISIT OR TREATMENT WITH DOCTOR WAS REQUIRED OR NEEDED, PER PHYSICIANS ORDERS. BOTH EMPLOYEES STATED  THEY WERE FINE.

column168: For reasons still unknown, the driver failed to negotiate the turn on the highway, which resulted in the transportation unit leaving the highway onto the shoulder and flatland area. The vehicle traveled approximately 317 feet until it struck a culvert and overturned. The resulting impact with the culvert caused a tear in the tanker causing the diesel fuel to leak from the vehicle. Approximately 614 gallons of diesel fuel leaked from the tanker into the ground surface. The area impacted by the release required excavation, water removal (high water table), replacement soils and compaction.
column169: There is still no evidence to suggest why the driver failed to make the turn in the roadway. Where experts have been unable to determine the cause of the accident, it is difficult to suggest what might prevent this type of incident from reoccurring. All drivers have regular safety training to help prevent any type of accident or HAZMAT release. Also, drivers have current DOT Medical Cards stating that they are fit for duty.

column168: ON OCTOBER 31, 2006, A TANK TRUCK OWNED AND OPERATED BY PENRECO WAS INVOLVED IN A VEHICULAR INCIDENT ON ROUTE 268 IN COWANSVILLE, PA AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 AM. THE   TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON ROUTE 268 WHEN A COLLISION WITH A PASSENGER VEHICLE   OCCURRED. THE TRUCK TURNED ON IT SIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 2,900 GALLONS OF WEAK ALKALI LIQUOR (WAL) WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANKER VESSEL. RELEASE FROM THE VESSEL WAS DUE TO DAMAGE THAT OCCURRED TO THE DOME COVER DURING THE ROLLOVER OF THE TANKER VESSEL. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIALS FROM THE TANKER VESSEL LASTED APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS. THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL IN THE OVERTURNED TANKER VESSEL WAS THEN TRANSFERRED TO A WAITING TANKER VESSEL. THE WAL FLOWED INTO A ROADSIDE DITCH, INTO A TRIBUTARY TO GLADE RUN CREEK, AND THEN INTO GLADE RUN CREEK (LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 1.2 MILES DOWNSTREAM FROM THE INCIDENT SITE).     WAL IS A BYPRODUCT OF PENRECO’S MINERAL OIL MANUFACTURING PROCESS. IT IS AN ALKALINE WATER THAT IS BENEFICIALLY USED FOR THE TREATMENT OF ACID MINE DRAINAGE (AMD) BY SITES THAT HAVE BEEN IMPACTED BY COAL MINING ACTIVITIES. THE ALKALINE WATER IS MIXED WITH AMD AT THE SITES TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACIDIC DRAINAGE AND IMPROVE THE QUALITY OF SURFACE WATER BEFORE IT IS DISCHARGED TO A RECEIVING STREAM. THE BYPRODUCT IS APPROVED FOR SUCH BENEFICIAL USE UNDER GENERAL PERMIT WMGRO8O. THE WAL WAS IN TRANSIT TO AN APPROVED MINE DRAINAGE SITE IN CADOGAN, PENNSYLVANIA.     IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT, SAND WAS DEPLOYED AT THE SITE TO CONTAIN ANY OIL THAT COULD HAVE BEEN RELEASED FROM THE ENGINE OR THE FUEL TANKS OF THE TRUCK. WITH THE EXCEPTION OF TWO GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL, NO HYDROCARBONS WERE RELEASED FROM THE VEHICLE. ALL OF THE HYDROCARBONS WERE ABSORBED BY THE SAND WITH THE EXCEPTIONS OF A FEW DROPLETS FOUND ON THE GROUND SURFACE NEAR THE SITE. ANY MATERIAL CONTAMINATED WITH HYDROCARBONS WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE IN A ROLL-OFF BOX AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT LANDFILL IN WEST SUNBURY, PENNSYLVANIA. AFTER THE REMOVAL OF THE SAND AND OTHER CONTAMINATED MATERIAL, THE DRAINAGE DITCH WAS FLUSHED WITH 1,500 GALLONS OF WATER FROM THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TANK TRUCK. THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE CLEAR IN THE MORNING BUT THEN RAIN BEGAN AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM AND LASTED THROUGHOUT THE EVENING RESULTING IN ADDITIONAL FLUSHING. OFFICIALS FROM THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION (PA DEP) WERE ON SITE AND WERE UPDATED REGARDING ANY PROGRESS AND CLEANUP EFFORTS THROUGHOUT THE DAY. THE OFFICIALS AGREED THAT THERE WAS NO FURTHER REMEDIAL ACTION REQUIRED DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE MATERIAL RELEASED INTO THE WATER.     THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE DISPATCHED AN ACCIDENT RECONSTRUCTION TEAM TO THE   INCIDENT SCENE TO GATHER INFORMATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT. TO DATE THIS FINAL REPORT HAS NOT BEEN RECEIVED BY PENRECO.     RESPONSE TO THE INCIDENT INCLUDED PENRECO PERSONNEL, ARMSTRONG COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF   PUBLIC SAFETY, EAST FRANKLIN TOWNSHIP POLICE DEP
column169: ONCE PENRECO HAS RECEIVED THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE ACCIDENT RECONSTRUCTION TEAMS FINAL REPORT NECESSARY ACTIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS WILL BE PUT INTO PLACE. A SUPPLEMENTAL (FOLLOW-UP) REPORT WELL BE SUBMITTED TO THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.

column168: Flying J Transportation unit was traveling westbound on 1-80 at milepost 327.10. Weather conditions were extreme ice fog with limited visibility. A tractor trailer had spun out and two other tractor trailer units had stopped to prevent hitting the unit. The Flying J unit came over the hill and noticed both units stopped on the interstate. The Flying J unit immediately veered to the right to avoid a rear end collision. While attempting the maneuver, the pup trailer collided with the trailer of the stopped tractor trailer unit causing a puncture in the pup trailer. As a result of impact, the rear compartment of the pup lost 1721 gallons of no-lead gasoline. Emergency response crews were immediately dispatched from the Denver, CO and Salt Lake City, UT areas. The fuel escaped the Pup and entered the adjacent shoulder and median soil.   Flying J Response Crews employed a vapor extraction system and recovered ll40 of the 1721 gallons lost. The remaining fuel was removed by excavation, escaped into the bedrock or through evaporation.
column169: Flying J Transportation drivers have been reminded to use judgment during bad weather conditions. In this case, the driver was proceeding 40 MPH in a 75 MPH zone. However, due to the small hill, and the fact that two trucks had stopped back to back, there was not sufficient room for the vehicle to make a safe stop due to the ice buildup on the road surface.     If weather conditions warrant, drivers will stop there vehicles at the nearest safety point and wait for weather conditions to improve.

column168: At approximately 0755 hours (local time) on 10-19-06 an unintentional release of oxygen, refrigerated liquid occurred at the Apria Healthcare branch at 255 N.W. Victoria Drive, Lees Summit, MO.    Apria employee John Bullington was in the process of filling a HL 190, non-specification cargo tank, mounted in the box on an Isuzu truck. When he attempted to close the stand tank fill line valve he found that the valve was frozen to the point he could not turn it. After making unsuccessful attempts to turn the valve he started to disengage the fill line. As the line came loose a flow of oxygen, refrigerated liquid commenced. As he was unable to close the stand tank valve he pointed the hose up into the air, between the vehicle and the stand tank, over the concrete parking area. He immediately yelled for assistance and a fellow employee contacted the supervisor who had notification made to the Lees Summit Fire Department. The surrounding area was immediately closed to all foot and vehicular traffic. Contact was made with the Apria Lenexa transfill facility for technical assistance and the required corporate notifications were made.    Upon arrival of the Lees Summit Fire Department they observed the incident and after contacting  EPA and DNR made the determination that the flow of oxygen, refrigerated liquid was low enough and that it was converting to vapor which was dispersing into an open field and did not constitute a hazard. They would stand by in case of an emergency until Apria staff could either close the valve or the leak terminated.    By approximately 0845 hours Dan Armstrong, Apria Transfill Supervisor had arrived and closed the valve, terminating the release. The fire department checked the area and determined that the situation was secure.    It was determined that approximately 1178 gallons of oxygen, refrigerated liquid had been released, converted to vapor and dispersed into the atmosphere.     There were no injuries or collateral damage.
column169: Immediately upon the fire departments assessment that the scene was secure a question and answer session was held with both the Apria staff and the on-scene members of the Lees Summit Fire Department. The functionality of the stand tank and the filling process were reviewed as well as actions to take in case of malfunctioning equipment.    Additional in-service training on the filling process and troubleshooting is being conducted with the Apria Healthcare staff .

Alfred was loading his first load and after loading for approx 10 minutes he observed a slight change in the tone if the loading pump. Just then the gasket on the left discharge valve blew out and sprayed oil forward on the :ruck and ground. Alfred was standing toward the rear of the discharge valve when it blew. The wind had blown oil spray back on him.
column169: Our mechanics will look into to this when we get it steamed out, It seems we had lost air prssure and that aused the belly line valve and vent to close while loading. Were not sure right now why the pump did not go into automatic by-pass when it encountered the pressure. Under investigation.

column62: Forklift Accident; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: I,Thomas Grudem, was checking the placards on a trailer and was down on the tarmac and noticed a puddle underneath the trailer 313-8144 that was docked in door 36. I went to check it out and it was emitting a very strong chemical smell and the ground was foaming. I immediately came back up on the dock and checked in the trailer. The trailer was empty. I then checked in the nose of the trailer for any residue and there was a small wet spot on the floor of the trailer and it also smelled of chemicals. I then questioned the DSR Afredo Beas (UST) whether he had noticed anything unusual while unloading the trailer and I informed him of the spill. He stated that he did not smell anything but did notice that the bottom of a pallet of boxes was wet. The DSR stated that the freight did not have any blocking or bracing around it. The freight was also placed on a substandard quality pallet and the box in question was on the corner bottom of the pallet. The pallet was listed as a leave on. The fact that the puddle was under the trailer leads me to believe that the freight was punctured while unloading.
column169: It is my recommendation that the DSR Alfredo Beas receive written discipline in regards to the handling of this freight.

column168: Tankcar TEIX 20014 was reported releasing vapors at the UPRR Alfalfa yard in El Paso, Texas. John Jackson, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, responded and discovered the release was due to a faulty vacuum relief device. Mr. Jackson notified Viva Environmental to respond. Viva personnel responded and removed the faulty vacuum relief devise and plugged the car with a stainless steel plug, stopping the release. The car was set out in the UPRR repair tracks pending shipper obtaining FRA Movement approval before forwarding to repair facility to replace the faulty vacuum relief device. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec.
column169: Shipper review loading and unloading inspection procedures.                         NARRI: 2(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 36                                            Code(s): 461

column168: Mark Barrios, Car Foreman, reported tank car GAPX 9022 was releasing a liquid substance on track 503, the RIP track, in the railroad yard in Livonia, LA. Mr. Barrios advised there were no reported injuries, derailments, or waterways affected. Thomas Robinson, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded.     Upon arrival, Robinson advised the release was from a   defect in the tank at the A end of the tank car, located above the truck assembly. It was dripping product at a rate of two to three drops per second. The defect was either a crack or from corrosion, but was unobservable do to tie jacket on the car. State notifications were made.     Mr. Robinson advised plastic was placed onto the ground and per David Riggs, Georgia Gulf, crews would arrive at a later time for transloading operations.     At 08:18 PM, Robinson advised Hulcher Services would be transloading the material to an empty compatible tank car, UTLX 71553, that had been located in the railroad yard. On 10/3/2006 at 4:01 AM, Robinson advised transloading efforts were completed and the leaking was stopped at 3:45 AM. Mr. Robinson further stated containment pads were placed underneath empty Tankcar GAPX 9022 to absorb the material dripping from the insulation inside the jacket and would be maintained as needed. State regulatory agencies were updated.

Theresa, Car Foreman, reported an unknown amount of product was released from Gondola UP 97524 inside the railyard in Colton, CA. Theresa stated the product was released to the ground. Robert Bavier, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and advised United Pumping was on scene for remediation. At 03:21 PM, Bavier advised the railcar was aged and rain water made contact with Lead Sulfide within the railcar and was releasing from the rusted out hole spots on the railcar. Mr. Bavier stated United Pumping Service was patching the damaged portions on the railcar. At 04:51 PM, Bavier advised repairs were completed and the release ceased. Mr. Bavier further advised the railcar was released to transportation.

UPRR s Response Management Communications Center notified Lane A. Sekavec, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety of a report of product released from totes at the One-Spot in Kansas City, KS.   ELKX 13106, flat with 30 residue totes (calcium carbide)   was reported by Car Foreman Rich Monger to have released some product onto the flat car. Mr. Monger said it appeared that the product had only been released during movement of the car and was not releasing product while sitting still.   Investigation by Mr.   Sekavec indicated that the product appeared to have been caked around the bottom outlet gates on the totes and then dropped onto the car when they were re-loaded after being emptied and during transit. The outlet gates on the totes all appeared to be closed and secure. Approximately five pounds of material was on the deck of the flat car.  The material on the flat car had already been neutralized by the moisture in the air and was removed from the car and disposed of. No other remediation was needed as there was no environmental impact.

column168: Driver Paul Taylor states that at 21:00 hrs on 10/11/06, Eastman started loading trailer # 7896. The shippers loading spout came loose due to a loose and defective fitting letting about 50 to 60 pounds of Piccotac tm 9095   HYDROCARBON RESIN spill into the crash box in top of the tank being loaded. Product drained into lining of tank. The loader stopped loading, cleaned up spill, and the driver called David Dygert at his home terminal at about 22:00 hrs to report spill. Loader finished loading tank. Driver said everything appeared to be alright. The driver left shipper (Eastman) at 0 1:30 hrs on 10/12/36. While in transit the trailer started smoking and caught fire inside lining due to the hot Product in the insulation. The driver put out fire with water and returned to the shop for inspection of trailer. The shipper was responsible for all loading and securing of the load.   I)ispatcher’s statement:   Driver, Paul Taylor, notified me at approximately 22:00 hrs on 10/11/06 that a small amount of Piccotac 9095 Hydrocarbon Resin (approximately 50 to 60 pounds) had been spilt into the crash box of trailer # 7896. Paul Taylor also stated that the loading spout had fallen apart and that Eastman was conducting the loading. Paul Taylor stated that the product was cleaned up and everything was OK. No report was initiated or required by Eastman. Loading resumed and delivery was started at approximately 09:55 on 10/12/06. Paul Taylor notified me that he had noticed that trailer # 7896 was smoking and stopped at mile marker 171 near Grayson, Ky. The insulation was smoldering under lining around the crash box. I dispatched mechanics, William Barber (shop foreman) and James Blankenship to the driver’s location. Using water they saturated the smoldering insulation and returned trailer # 7896 to the Kenova terminal where additional shop personnel continued to monitor the trailer. At 17:00 hrs after shop personnel was convinced that the insulation was secure, trailer 7896 was connected to shore power until delivery could be completed on 10/14/06.

THIS STATEMENT WAS TAKEN OVER THE PHONE FROM SHANNON BRUNSON.  AT AROUND 7PM (1900 HRS) HE WAS GETTING READY TO LOAD A TOTE OF LOSURF 300.  HE STATED THAT THIS TOTE IS NOT AN ORIGINAL TOTE FROM THIS YARD, IT HAS A DIFFERENT SHAPE.  HE PULLED THE TOTE FROM THE WAREHOUSE AND PUT THE TOTE ON THE SCALE.  HE RECORDED THE VOLUME WHICH WAS 350 GAL.  HE THEN SAT THE TOTE DOWN OUTSIDE TO REPOSITION HIS FORKLIFT.  HE PUT THE FORKS UNDER THE TOTE.  THEN HE STARTED TO PICK UP THE TOTE AND THE TOTE SHIFTED, WHICH IS NORMAL FOR THE OTHER STYLE OF TOTES.  THE TOTE THEN TILTED FORWARD AND FELL OFF THE FORKS.  HE HAD ONLY MOVED ABOUT 1 FOOT.  HE WAS STILL ON THE GRAVEL.  HE THEN MOVED TO THE FRONT OF THE TOTE & PUT ONE OF THE FORKS IN THE OPENING OF THE TOTE.  CHRIS HELPED HIM SET THE TOTE UPRIGHT.  THEN STARTED CONTAINING THE SPILL AND CALLED THE PROPER PEOPLE.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: FRA Inspector, E. Staehlin noted tank car CITX 34532 (Residue Last Contained Petroleum Gases, Liquefied) leaking. He noted a vapor leak at the vapor line valve due to the valve being open 1/4 turn and its plug being less than tool tight. He closed this valve. He noted the plug for the “B” end liquid line valve was less than hand tight. CSX Transportation dispatched Sunpro to inspect and insure all deficiencies had been corrected and that: CITX 34532 was in proper condition for transportation.       NARRI:5(1+5+O)x(2+O)=60   Cause Code: 249

column62: Human Error; Corrosion - Interior; Threads Worn or Cross Threaded
column168: On 10/03/2006, at 20:l8hrs, CSX Transportation Hazardous Materials received a call from Train Master, Phil Krauss reporting an odor coming from ACFX 78009 in the CSX Collier Yard in Petersburg, VA. CSX Transportation dispatched Hepaco Environmental (John Francisco 804-363-4957) to investigate. Hepaco arrived on site and discovered a faint odor coming from the suspected tank car. After further investigation it was discovered that the manway gasket was not seated correctly in the manway cover due to rust build up. It was also determined that one manway bolt was stripped and would not stay tool tight. Hepaco changed out the manway gasket and replaced it with a nozzle gasket and tightened the manway as tight as it would allow. The car was placed in bad order status awaiting the shipper to get the stripped manway bolt replaced. Car was moved around yard and no visible odors or product were visible.     Chemtrec Report # 10032006102     Cause Code 205 & 208     NARRI= 5(5+1+0) (2+0) =60

On 10/03/06 at 11:19 hours, General Foreman, Gary Frey, called the PSCC to report an odor in the train yard at the Queens Gate Yard, Cincinnati, Ohio. GATX 71768 was inspected and found to be the source of the leak. Inspection of GATX 71768 found the car was leaking vapors from a loose packing gland nut on the top operating rod for the bottom outlet valve. The packing gland nut was tightened and the odor subsided. All other valves and fittings on the car were checked for leaks and found secured. The car was released to destination.       NARRI: 2 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24     Cause Code: 296

column168: COPIED FROM POLICE REPORT    DRIVER #1 JAMES T. FOX (OUTSIDE INDIVIDUAL)  DRIVER #2 CHRIS HICKS (UNIVAR EMPLOYEE)    BOTH VEHICLES, ONE AND TWO WERE TRAVELING WEST ON I-24. VEHICLE TOW IN THE RIGHT LANE, VEHICLE ONE IN THE LEFT LANE. VEHICLE ONE WAS ATTEMPTING TO PASS VEHICLE TWO. VEHICLE ONE LOST CONTROL. THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE ONE OVER CORRECTED, STRIKING VEHICLE TWO. CAUSING TWO TO RUN OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. VEHICLE TOW ROLLED OVER AS IT ENTERED THE MEDIAN. WHEN VEHICLE ONE STRUCK OUR TANKER, IT CAUSED OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER TO O’IERTURN. THE UNIT CAME TO A REST ON THE DRIVER SIDE. THIS TANKER HAD 5 COMPARTMENTS. LOCATED ON THE DOME LID ON TOP, IS A 2 INCH THREADED FITTING. A 2 INCH CAP WITH GASKET IS PLACED ON THE FITTING. THE LEAK FOR EACH PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THESE FITTINGS. ONCE? FIRST RESPONSE (CLEAN UP COMPANY) WERE ON THE SCENE AND MADE THE INITIAL ENTRY, THEY WERE ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE 2 FITTINGS WITH A WRENCH AND STOP THE LEAKS. THE LEAKS WERE THE SIZE OF THE TIP OF AN INK PEN.  ANOTHER UNIT WAS BROUGHT IN AND WE TRANSFERRED THE MATERIAL FROM THE WRECKED UNIT TO THE OTHER UNIT. WHEN THE UNIT RETURNED, IT WAS WEIGHED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 226 POUNDS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS LOST FROM THE 2 THAT WERE LEAKING. THE MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO AN AREA APPROXIMATELY 1O’ x 15’. ONCE THE TANKER WAS UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED, FIRST RESPONSE EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED GROUND AND PLACED IN A ROLL OFF BOX. BOTH TRUCK/TRAILER AND ROLL OFF BOX WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE UNIVAR MURIREESBORO FACILITY FOR LATER DISPOSITION.

column168: On 10/26/06 at 05:30 hrs., a car inspector was working on an outbound train at the CSXT train yard in Russell , KY and reported a chlorine odor coming from residue tank car GATX 46566 or PPGX 1713. The two tank cars were safely isolated in the yard and the emergency response plan was activated. A CSXT contractor was dispatched to the scene to inspect the cars. GATX 46566 was found with the liquid valve on the A end in the open position. It took 1/2 a turn to close the valve. Both the A and B liquid valve plugs were not installed. The plugs were replaced and tool tightened. Using an ammonia solution, it was confirmed that the leak was stopped. The PPGX 1713 was inspected and found not to be leaking. The shipper was notifed via Chemtrac report number 10262006020.  NARRI: 5(4+10+1) X (2+0) = 150  Cause Code= 311

At approximately 1450 operations received a call about a bag that was leaking what smelled like finger nail polish remover. The MOD and ramp supervisor went to B5 to investigate and the city of phoenix hazmat department was called.  The passengers were deplaned and the fire department, city of phoenix police department and the hazmat team arrived and assessed the bag and the 32 oz bottle of broken "l2000 liquid"  Methylmethacrylate monomer. the police escorted the pax,  Giang Tran, to the ramp area to be questioned. They discovered 3 other 32 oz bottles of the same liquid in his bag. Roy Morales, FAA, contacted operations and asked that I contact  Craig Burns, the Regional FAA HAZMAT inspector, I was unable to contact Craig Burns and called Mr. Morales back and inquired what evidence I needed to obtain from the scene. Mr. Morales informed me to call Michael Givens, the supervisor at the National Response Center. I called Mr. Givens at 1708. He conferenced Mr. William Clark and I explained the details of the incident. I provided the flight number, aircraft type/number, passenger information (including pax itineray, address, phone number and bag claim number). Mr. Givens and Mr. Clark advised me to take pictures of the HAZMAT and send an initial report with the pictures to Mr. Clark. They informed me Mr. Craig Burns would be at the station on F 5800 form.     Pax Info: Glang Tran record locator BOILB4 (HP217, HP2889)            14402 janice street            westminister, ca 92683      cell (714) 837-1935  work (714) 279-8196  faa officials:  Michael Givens 310-725-3300                  Roy Morales 602-794-3148                  William Clark 650-826-128
