column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: Car GPPX 9520 was found leaking Formaldehyde Solutions from the top of the car while trainman Mr. Ragle was riding the end of this car. Mr. Ragle was splashed on the head and chest area, washed off at the site, and transported back to hotel where he took a shower and changed clothes. He talked to CTEH and decided to be checked out at the local hospital where he was released to go back to work. SWS was contacted to inspect and repair car. Their investigation found one bolt loose on the manway next to the hinge. Gasket was inspected and found to be in proper condition. The manway was resecured and car was cleaned. The next lay the car was shaken to inspect for leaks, and it was noted the manway still was leaking. SWS were called back tc the car and it was found leaking at the manway gasket area where the manway gasket had slipped. A nozzle gasket was installed, car was moved and no leak found. Car was released to move forward.  CAUSE CODE: 200  NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+2) = 160

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On 10/19/2006 at 12:16 hrs., CSX Transportation Hazardous Materials Systems, Ed Cook (904-381-2212), was notified of an odor from ECUX 575043 by Train Master Greathouse (803-206-6483). The car was located in the CSXT Cayce Yard in Cayce, South Carolina. CSXT HazMat dispatched Hepaco Inc. (Bob BaKter 800-888-7689)  respond. Hepaco arrived on site and met with CSXT persomiel and discovered, after checking with a soapy water solution, that the B End liquid valve plug was loose. It was also discovered that the 4 bolts on the face plate of the liquid valve were also less than tool tight. Hepaco tightened face plate bolts, and opened and losed valve to reseat. After valve was reseated, Hepaco checked for leaks and discovered that all leaks had stopped The plug was tightened tool tight and car was released for transportation.  Chemtrec Report # 10192006044  Cause Code: 317  NARRI: 5(5+7+0)(2+0) = 120

During a routine yard inspection at the Memphis Jct.Yard, Bowling Green, KY., Hazardous Material Manager, Jim Briski, inspected rail car PTLX 223670, product was found on both sides of the rail car. Inspection found 6 of the 8 manway bolts were less than tool tight. The manway was opened, inspected for defects and properly closed and sealed. The car was sent to destination for unloading. Chemtrec was notified #10242006057..  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) =60  Cause Code = 200

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: That day it was raining a lot, also the road is very narrow. When Mr. Jove arrived at Km. 9.0 cars were coming from the opposite direction, that is why he stopped at the edge of the road. After releasing the brakes to continue driving, the truck tractor started to slip toward the hill on his right side. Mr. Jove tried to take it out of the edge, but the truck tractor continued to slide down. Mr. Jove jumped out of the truck tractor. The truck tractor continued turning around downhill. The truck tractor and the tank rolled over 270 degrees and stopped resting on the left side. The product was released by three manhole covers. Product released stayed in the site area. Most of the product was picked up with absorbent material. Approximately 7950 gallons were transferred to another cargo tank. An environmental company performed the clean up and removal of contaminated soil.

HE SHIPPED ONE OF TWO 5 GAL PAILS ONTO THE SHIPPER.

The other vehicle pulled out to pass the north bound vehicle stricking our vehicle head on. After impact both vehicles veered to the left crossing the north bound lane and over turning. The tanker came to rest on its side in the bar ditch on Little Glasses Rd. on top of a metal telephone cable box.  The box cut holes in the tanker side causing the spill. January Transportation out of Oklahoma City was hired to clean up spill area.

Mike Hale, Car Foreman, Montgomery, AL., reported GATX 45074, load of Sodium Aluminate, Solution, in the shop area with a white residue on the sides of the tank. CSX’s inspection of the car found the rupture disk had deployed and inspection cap was missing. CSX responded SWS to make the proper repairs to the car. A new rupture disk was installed and the inspection cap was placed over the disk to hold it in place. Other parts of the assembly were missing, therefore, the shipper was notified and advised that the car shop from GATX would have to make the final repairs before the car could move in transportation. The shipper agreed to make arrangements with a repair facility before forwarding the car.  CAUSE CODE -441  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: Manager Cooper was contacted by Transloading Environmental, advising they had been contacted by APL to inspect a leaking container. Developed container TRLU 413735 contained approximately 20 floor loaded pallets of 5 gallon pails of  various ‘distressed’ or ‘returned’ paint products. The 5 gallon pails were stacked and stretch wrapped to the pallets. All were distressed or leaking. All of the leaking pails were placed into salvage drums for securement. Numerous pails were so severely stressed that they were no longer fit for further transportation. The stressed pails were also placed into salvage drums for securement. The residue paint was cleaned and the lading placed back into the original container for movement onto the consignee.
column169: Ensure containers are in proper condition for shipment.

column168: Theresa, Car Foreman, reported an unknown amount of product was released from Gondola UP 97536 inside the railyard in Colton, CA. Theresa stated the product was released to the ground. Robert Bavier, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and advised United Pumping was on scene for remediation. At 03:21 PM, Bavier advised the railcar was aged and rain water made contact with product within the railcar and was releasing from the rusted out hole spots on the railcar. Mr. Bavier stated United Pumping Service was patching the damaged portions on the railcar. At 04:51 PM, Bavier advised repairs were completed and the release ceased. Mr. Bavier further advised the railcar was released to transportation.

column168: Manager Cooper was contacted by Transloading Environmental, advising they had been contacted by APL to inspect a leaking container. Developed container TGHU 732327 contained 20 pallets, floor loaded, with loose one gallon cans of ‘distressed’ or ‘returned’ paint. The one gallon cans were stacked and stretch wrapped to the pallets, and were not loaded into DOT approved boxes for shipment. Approximately 220 of the one gallon cans were leaking or damaged to the point that they were no longer fit for further transportation. All the damaged leaking cans were placed into salvage drums to properly secure them. The residue paint was cleaned and the lading placed back into the original container for movement onto the consignee.

column58: Cover; O-Ring or Seals; Vacuum Relief Valve
column168: At l200hrs on 10-6-06, Frank Lerch, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was contacted by Dave Raschio, Director of Terminal Operations. He advised a local switch crew had reported an odor coming from loaded tank car UTLX 660506 located on the south end of bowl track 8 Settegast Yard; Houston, TX.   Upon inspection of car in company with Tim 0 Brien, Regional Manager Chemical   Transportation Safety, it was determined the 0-ring in the vacuum relief valve had failed causing vapor to leak from the car. After determining source of the release, Mgr. Lerch advised the RMCC to make shipper notification via Chemtrec. Mgr. Lerch and 0 Brien then replaced the valve with a solid plug which secured the car from further release, and enabled the car to continue onto destination without further incident.   At approximately l400hrs, Mgr. Lerch spoke to shipper contact Debra Hooper, Global Transportation   Regional Manager for Lubrizol advising her of the release and corrective action taken. Mgr. Lerch further advised Ms. Hooper after the car is off loaded, it should shopped for further inspection, and have a vacuum relief valve reinstalled on the car.

column58: Frangible Disc; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Dean Cooper, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, reported he was en route to the Los Nietos Yard located in Santa Fe Springs, CA. FRA Inspector Jack Vail, had observe red residue product on the sides of a unknown tank car in the yard and had reported the alleged release. At 04:21 PM, Manager Cooper advised tank car GATX 47190 had released product while in transit. The product had dried and formed a residue on the top and sides of the tank car. Inspection noted a blown frangible disc in the top mounted GATX safety tri-vent. The inspection cap was missing from the top of the safety vent, which allowed the product to geyser out the top of the car while in movement. A like type BS&B 165 pound stainless frangible disc was placed in the safety vent, which secured the leak. The car was set to an adjacent track where it could be cleaned of the residue, which was accomplished on 10/26/06. The car was then released for movement onto the consignee.

column168: Chad Crabtree, Yardmaster, reported six railcars derailed in the Livonia railyard at approximately Mile Post 112.00 of the Livonia Subdivision. Mr. Crabtree advised three tankcars were hazmat loads and Tankcar UTLX 300815 is possibly releasing product. Mr. Crabtree advised Hazmat Tankcars, UTLX 300815, GATX 56095, and empty residue ACFX 73384, were derailed on their sides. Thomas Robinson, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. State and federal notifications were made. At 04:23 AM, Robinson advised he was on scene at Tankcar UTLX 300815, and there was a clear nonodorous liquid releasing from the protective housing, which was at a 5 o clock position. Mr. Robinson advised the tankcar was rolled over and there was approximately two gallons of product on the ground. The leak was a small stream of product coming from the vacuum relief valve. At 7:26 AM, Robinson advised Tankcar UTLX 300815 had been uprighted and the release of material had stopped. Railcars ACFX 73384 and GATX 56095 were also rerailed. Neither car lost any product.

column168: Jim Heronimus, Manager of Yard Operations, Union Pacific Railroad, El Paso, Tx. Reported yard personnel at the rip track in the Alfalfa Yard detected a strong odor in the vicinity of Tankcar GATX 16277, however did not observe venting or a release of material. Dennis Johnson, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, Union Pacific Railroad was contacted and stated he would contract Viva Environmental of El Paso to respond to the report. Johnson reported the car was checked and found to have four of the eight manway bolts not secured properly, resulting in a minor release of product. Mr. Johnson stated there was a product moisture buildup near one of the manway bolts, which had caused the odor. Mr. Johnson advised the bolts were secured properly, the moisture was cleaned, and the car was released to transportation.

THIS CAME IN FROM THE EAST SO I WOULD IMAGIN THE TIME FRAME OF THE RELEASE WAS OVER 20 HOURS. column168: ON OCTOBER 27, 2006 AT 10:45, A BAG WAS ON THE BAG CAROUSEL IN UNITED AIRLINES OUTBOUND BAGROOM AND FOUND TO BE SPILLING AN UNKNOWN LIQUID. THE BAG WAS PULLED OFF THE BAG CAROUSEL ONTO THE BAG ROOM FLOOR WHERE A 4’ X 5’ FEET SPILL WAS CREATED. TSA DID NOT GET A CHANCE TO SCREEN THE BAG AS IT WAS TAKEN OFF THE BELT CAROUSEL AS SOON AS IT ARRIVED INTO THE BAGROOM FROM THE TICKET COUNTER. WE STARTED THE IMMEDIATE RESPONSE PROCESS BY HAVING ALL EMPLOYEES LEAVE THE AREA AND WE CONTACTED THE LOCAL PORT POLICE AND HAZARD MATERIAL DEPTS. THE PORT POLICE QUESTIONED THE PSGR AND THE ITEM WAS FOUND TO BE A CONCENTRATED FORM OF ACETONE IN A 32-OUNCE GLASS BOTTLE, WHICH HAD BROKEN WHILE IN THE BAG. THE PORT AUTHORITY HAZARD DEPT ALSO SEARCHED THE PSGR’S OTHER BAGGAGE AND FOUND NOTHING ELSE HAZARDOUS. THE PORT AUTHORITY HAZARD DEPT CLEANED UP THE SPILL IN THE BAGROOM AND FANS WERE PLACED INSIDE THE BAGROOM TO ALLOW FOR MORE VENTILATION TO ALLEVIATE THE ODOR. THE 8 EMPLOYEES WORKING IN THE BAGROOM AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL WERE SENT TO PORT MEDICAL FOR EVALUATION. ALL WERE RELEASED WITHOUT ANY INJURIES OR INCIDENT. THE PORT AUTHORITY HAZARD DEPT DECLARED THE SPILL TO BE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BUT NOT A HEALTH RISK AND THE BAGROOM WAS ALLOWED TO BE RE-OPENED AT 1:00 PM; EMPLOYES WERE ALLOWED BACK INTO THE BAGROOM. THE PASSENGER WAS TRAVELING ON FLT 805 TO NRT. THE PASSENGER WAS INTERVIEWED BY PORT POLICE AND RELEASED TO TRAVEL ON HER ORIGINAL FLIGHT WITH THE 3 REMAINING BAGS.
column169: PASSENGERS SHOULD BE ENCOURAGED TO DISCLOSE ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN THEIR BAGGAGE AND BE ADVISED OF LEGALITIES FOR NOT DISCLOSING.     REPORT IS FILED AS REQUIRED BY 49CFR 175.31

column168: Tankcar GATX 18534 was reported to be emitting an odor. The tank car was inspected and it was discovered that the manway gasket was deteriorated to the point where it was not sealing properly and allowing product to drip onto the side of the railcar. The car was set out and temporarily sealed until the proper manway gasket was received from the shipper, at which time it was replaced. The tank car was released to continue to destination.
column169: Inspect and replace gasket more often at the first signs of wear.

column168: RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY AND REPORTED A SWITCHMAN WAS MOVING TANKCAR GATX 22272 INSIDE THE MILLER YARD IN DALLAS, TX, WHEN PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE TANKCAR AND ONTO THE SWITCHMAN’S NECK. THE SWITCHMAN COMPLAINED OF AN IRRITATION ON HIS NECK, WHICH HE WAS TREATING BY WASHING IT WITH WATER. KELLY RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR FOUND THAT SEVEN OF THE EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT AND THAT THE CAR HAD THE WRONG SIZE MANWAY GASKET IN IT. KELLY REPLACED THE MANWAY GASKET AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS. AFTER A COMPLETE INSPECTION THE CAR IT WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTITATION.

column168: OFFICE MANAGER, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM RAILCAR YFSZ 116851, LOCATED AT PAD S INSIDE THE INTERMODAL FACILITY IN MESQUITE, TX. EMPLOYEE STATED THE RAILCAR BELONGED TO YELLOW FREIGHT AND THEY HAD CONTACTED THEIR OWN HAZMAT TEAM FOR REMEDIATION. THE MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED. AT 02:53 PM, EMPLOYEE OFFICE MANAGER, ADVISED MILTON WALL, YELLOW FREIGHT, DISPATCHED TAS HAZMAT CLEANUP, CONTRACTOR, WHO WAS ON SCENE TO REMEDIATE THE FOUR SMALL PUDDLES OF PRODUCT FROM THE ASPHALT. MANAGER OF ENV. FIELD OPS., WAS ADVISED BY SPILL SITE SUPERVISOR OF TAS ENVIRONMENTAL THAT THE SOURCE OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS FROM A DRUM OF RESIN SOLUTION THAT WAS PUNCTURED BY A NAIL IN THE PALLET. TAS UNLOADED THE TRAILER BY SKY TRACK LIFT TO SECURE THE DRUM AND CLEANUP THE RESIDUE FROM THE TRAILER.
